WEBVTT

00:02.085 --> 00:03.378
Dylan:
Man, this looks crazy.

00:03.378 --> 00:04.880
Ray, you're the engineer
in the family.

00:04.880 --> 00:06.590
Ours is safe, right?

00:06.590 --> 00:08.091
[ Knock on door ]

00:08.091 --> 00:09.801
Oh, yeah.
This checks out.

00:09.801 --> 00:11.470
The helmet's overkill.

00:11.470 --> 00:13.597
Down the ramp,
jump over the dishes.

00:13.597 --> 00:14.556
We're good to go.

00:16.266 --> 00:18.477
Now, JJ, remember ‐‐
be...

00:18.477 --> 00:20.270
careful!

00:20.270 --> 00:21.104
Oh, no!

00:21.104 --> 00:22.272
JJ!

00:23.690 --> 00:24.775
Ouch!

00:24.775 --> 00:25.859
The ramp didn't work
so much.

00:25.859 --> 00:26.777
What happened?

00:26.777 --> 00:28.904
What's going on?!

00:28.904 --> 00:31.323
I step out for one minute,
and this is what you do?!

00:31.323 --> 00:33.367
You told me
this was a sculpture, Dylan.

00:33.367 --> 00:35.410
I complimented you
on it!

00:35.410 --> 00:37.788
And you broke
the chair!

00:37.788 --> 00:40.290
"They said
it was okay."

00:40.290 --> 00:42.626
They are children, JJ.
You should know better.

00:42.626 --> 00:44.545
"No ‐‐ <i>them."</i>

00:45.963 --> 00:48.006
They wanted Dylan
to be the dishes.

00:48.006 --> 00:49.883
I stopped that.

00:52.636 --> 00:55.555
♪♪

00:55.555 --> 00:57.057
That's what they sent?

00:57.057 --> 00:58.016
That's the new wheelchair?

00:58.016 --> 00:59.601
It looks used.

00:59.601 --> 01:02.187
It <i>is.</i> And it's what insurance
would pay for.

01:02.187 --> 01:04.648
How does it feel?

01:04.648 --> 01:05.440
Oh!

01:05.440 --> 01:06.567
Dude, what are
you doing?

01:06.567 --> 01:07.985
I‐It's got a mind
of its own.
Oh!

01:07.985 --> 01:09.570
Yeah, you want to go, chair?
Let's go!

01:09.570 --> 01:11.280
W‐‐ Okay.

01:11.280 --> 01:13.031
Okay, just ‐‐ There's a thing
on the back.
Yeah.

01:13.031 --> 01:15.576
Uh ‐‐ eh ‐‐
Go ahead.

01:15.576 --> 01:17.494
This is a joke.
We need the one he had.

01:17.494 --> 01:18.620
Can you call your guy
at insurance?

01:18.620 --> 01:20.122
Yeah, I'll take Stu
to lunch.

01:20.122 --> 01:21.707
Oh, you've got
an insurance hook‐up?
Oh, you have to.

01:21.707 --> 01:22.791
You have to
work your way in

01:22.791 --> 01:24.334
and help them understand
your situation.

01:24.334 --> 01:26.044
Otherwise, you end up
with the basics.

01:26.044 --> 01:27.629
And they won't pay
for a lot of your medications,

01:27.629 --> 01:29.298
therapies, equipment.

01:29.298 --> 01:30.757
Yeah, having a disability's
expensive.

01:30.757 --> 01:32.676
It's almost
not even worth it.
[ Laughs ]

01:32.676 --> 01:35.804
Luckily, I have never met
a claims rep I can't win over.

01:35.804 --> 01:37.431
And Stu's the easiest.

01:37.431 --> 01:39.600
He loves hearing about
my colorful English family.

01:39.600 --> 01:41.602
[ Cockney accent ] And leaning
into me cool, blimey, gov'nor,

01:41.602 --> 01:43.979
black‐cab Britishness
is fun, innit?

01:46.565 --> 01:47.649
Was that a question?

01:47.649 --> 01:50.652
♪♪

01:50.652 --> 01:52.487
What's that, Ray?

01:52.487 --> 01:55.073
Oh, nothing. Just my new
state‐of‐the‐art hoverboard.

01:55.073 --> 01:57.326
You're getting a hoverboard?
<i>I</i> want one.

01:57.326 --> 01:58.869
I'm not gonna be
the only DiMeo kid

01:58.869 --> 02:01.747
walking around on two legs,
like some ‐‐ some fool.

02:01.747 --> 02:03.165
Well, it's not mine <i>yet.</i>

02:03.165 --> 02:05.292
But there's an essay contest
going on at school

02:05.292 --> 02:06.585
with a cash prize.

02:06.585 --> 02:08.086
The topic's "My Hero."

02:08.086 --> 02:10.130
I'm just gonna write something
about growing up with JJ

02:10.130 --> 02:12.716
and ‐‐ Whoosh! ‐‐
slam dunk!

02:12.716 --> 02:14.760
Is that what you think
a slam dunk looks like?

02:16.136 --> 02:18.221
Does JJ know
you're doing this?
No.

02:18.221 --> 02:19.931
Well, shouldn't you
ask him?

02:19.931 --> 02:23.727
JJ, do you mind if I write an
essay about you being my hero?

02:23.727 --> 02:25.604
Maya:
He says, "No. That's stupid."

02:25.604 --> 02:27.356
What?!

02:27.356 --> 02:29.191
What the hell?!
Why not?

02:29.191 --> 02:32.569
"Because
I'm not your hero."

02:32.569 --> 02:35.405
So? Everybody's gonna cry.
I'm gonna get a hoverboard.

02:35.405 --> 02:36.782
Stop being a butthead.

02:36.782 --> 02:40.786
"I don't want you
lying about me

02:40.786 --> 02:43.246
to look good and win M‐O ‐‐

02:43.246 --> 02:44.790
money."

02:44.790 --> 02:46.958
Great. Now I have to find
a <i>real</i> hero.

02:46.958 --> 02:48.168
Who am I gonna
write about?

02:48.168 --> 02:50.212
Write about your dad.

02:50.212 --> 02:52.089
He left graduate school
and a promising career

02:52.089 --> 02:55.467
to take a job to provide
for his young, disabled son.

02:55.467 --> 02:58.345
Mom, please!
This is no time for jokes!

02:58.345 --> 03:00.514
Fine! I'll think
of something.

03:00.514 --> 03:02.641
Hopefully, next year, the topic
will be "Biggest Jerk."

03:02.641 --> 03:04.643
♪♪

03:04.643 --> 03:07.312
Ooh, Ray! Be careful!
He's not controlling the chair!

03:07.312 --> 03:08.397
Uh, yes, he is.

03:08.397 --> 03:09.773
Stop!
You're not a jerk!

03:09.773 --> 03:11.733
[ Both laughing ]

03:11.733 --> 03:15.278
Oh, Stu, thank you for letting
me treat you to lunch.

03:15.278 --> 03:17.864
Okay, so, what is the latest
with your wacky family?

03:17.864 --> 03:20.325
Would you do your impression
of your cousin Roger for me?

03:20.325 --> 03:21.535
Oh, yeah.

03:21.535 --> 03:24.121
[ Deep voice ] I'm Roger.
[ Laughs ] That's...

03:24.121 --> 03:25.664
[ English accent ]
"I'm Roger."

03:25.664 --> 03:26.915
Very deep.

03:26.915 --> 03:28.750
[ Normal voice ] Ohh.

03:28.750 --> 03:31.211
Mayaaa!
Stuuu!

03:31.211 --> 03:33.713
It's the least I could do.
We take care of each other.

03:33.713 --> 03:36.675
Which reminds me ‐‐
now, what is all this

03:36.675 --> 03:39.845
with the refurbished wheelchair
nonsense?

03:39.845 --> 03:41.138
Oh, you didn't hear.

03:41.138 --> 03:43.306
Oh, no, I‐I don't cover
health insurance anymore.

03:43.306 --> 03:44.850
I'm sorry ‐‐ What?
Got transferred.

03:44.850 --> 03:46.476
What?
To boats.

03:46.476 --> 03:48.228
Bloody boats?
Mm‐hmm.

03:48.228 --> 03:49.521
Why didn't you just tell me
on the phone?

03:49.521 --> 03:51.273
Did you think
I just wanted to hang out?

03:51.273 --> 03:52.649
No, no, I know
how the world works,

03:52.649 --> 03:55.652
and, to be honest,
I just figured you got a boat.

03:55.652 --> 03:57.404
Okay, well,
for health insurance,

03:57.404 --> 03:58.697
you just have to contact
my replacement.

03:58.697 --> 03:59.865
Her name is Janet.

03:59.865 --> 04:02.576
But be warned ‐‐
She is a tough nut to crack.

04:02.576 --> 04:03.869
Is she?
Yeah.

04:03.869 --> 04:05.537
I like a challenge.
Mm‐hmm.

04:05.537 --> 04:07.706
Well, it wasn't too long ago
that I was being warned

04:07.706 --> 04:11.168
about <i>another</i> tough nut,
by the name of Stu.

04:11.168 --> 04:12.335
That's not true,
is it?

04:12.335 --> 04:13.420
Nope.

04:13.420 --> 04:16.590
♪♪

04:16.590 --> 04:18.133
[ School bell rings ]

04:18.133 --> 04:19.551
Thank you.

04:19.551 --> 04:22.804
"And that is why,
just as E equals MC squared,

04:22.804 --> 04:25.807
Albert Einstein equals
my hero."

04:25.807 --> 04:27.642
Sorry to eavesdrop?

04:27.642 --> 04:30.312
But you really didn't sound
connected to the material?

04:30.312 --> 04:31.938
At least I don't say
every sentence

04:31.938 --> 04:33.815
like it's a question,
Kayla.

04:33.815 --> 04:35.984
I feel like
you're attacking me?

04:35.984 --> 04:38.487
Because you know
what I'm saying is true?

04:38.487 --> 04:41.281
Our next semi‐finalist
is Donald Bronson.

04:43.617 --> 04:47.329
"My Hero" ‐‐ It's a pretty easy
essay topic, right?

04:47.329 --> 04:49.915
I could come up here and give
you the obvious answers ‐‐

04:49.915 --> 04:51.958
Abraham Lincoln, Einstein.

04:51.958 --> 04:53.418
[ Scoffs ]

04:53.418 --> 04:55.587
Instead, I'm gonna talk to you
about someone

04:55.587 --> 04:58.715
whose strength of character
inspires me every day ‐‐

04:58.715 --> 05:01.384
my friend JJ DiMeo.

05:02.677 --> 05:05.055
I don't think
JJ even knows this kid.

05:05.055 --> 05:07.474
Then his performance
is impressive?

05:07.474 --> 05:09.976
'Cause he seems really connected
to the material?

05:09.976 --> 05:13.647
♪♪

05:13.647 --> 05:14.856
So, what's your plan
with this lady?

05:14.856 --> 05:16.024
Oh, it'll be easy.

05:16.024 --> 05:17.567
[ Pleasantly ] Hello.

05:17.567 --> 05:19.820
I'd like to see Janet
in claims.

05:19.820 --> 05:21.112
I'm a client.

05:21.112 --> 05:22.280
Do you have
an appointment?

05:22.280 --> 05:23.532
I don't.

05:23.532 --> 05:27.118
But I do have pictures
of my son on Santa's lap

05:27.118 --> 05:28.578
nine years in a row.

05:28.578 --> 05:30.831
I'm sorry.
Janet is booked solid.

05:30.831 --> 05:32.874
I completely understand.

05:32.874 --> 05:35.752
Okay. Just a moment.

05:35.752 --> 05:38.505
We need an appointment.
I guess that's that.

05:38.505 --> 05:39.673
Got it.

05:40.507 --> 05:41.508
Now.

05:41.508 --> 05:43.510
♪♪

05:43.510 --> 05:44.719
Delivery man:
Thanks very much.

05:46.513 --> 05:47.764
All right.

05:47.764 --> 05:50.225
Who is this tough nut?

05:50.225 --> 05:52.394
Based on all the pictures,

05:52.394 --> 05:54.437
she's either a woman
who loves this horse

05:54.437 --> 05:56.106
or a horse
who loves this woman.

05:56.106 --> 05:57.315
Can I help you?

05:57.315 --> 05:59.025
You must be Janet.
My name is ‐‐

05:59.025 --> 06:00.318
No need to tell me
your name.

06:00.318 --> 06:02.070
Just tell me
your account number.

06:02.070 --> 06:03.905
Oh, what makes you think
we're ‐‐ we're clients?

06:03.905 --> 06:06.241
Nine out of 10 people
who walk into this office

06:06.241 --> 06:09.327
are clients here to sweet‐talk
me into special treatment.

06:09.327 --> 06:12.289
Ohhh. You figured us out.
I'm sorry.

06:12.289 --> 06:13.874
We just want to help
our son.

06:13.874 --> 06:16.126
Out of those nine,
seven pretend to drop the act

06:16.126 --> 06:17.919
and make
a sincere‐sounding appeal,

06:17.919 --> 06:19.588
usually with a picture
of their child.

06:20.755 --> 06:24.175
Look, I find the people who
come in here asking for things

06:24.175 --> 06:27.178
are usually the people who are
already getting too much.

06:27.178 --> 06:29.389
So, again,
account number?

06:29.389 --> 06:31.892
Yeah, we don't need
to give you that.

06:31.892 --> 06:34.269
♪♪

06:34.269 --> 06:36.313
Well,
she was awful.

06:36.313 --> 06:39.024
How am I possibly going to
connect with her?

06:39.024 --> 06:42.152
You can't. And we will never
set foot in this office again.

06:42.152 --> 06:45.906
Right. We will never set foot
in this office again.

06:45.906 --> 06:49.075
Maya, are you choosing
to adhere to the letter

06:49.075 --> 06:50.827
but not the spirit
of what I'm saying?

06:50.827 --> 06:53.371
♪♪

06:53.371 --> 06:54.164
Janet!

06:55.749 --> 06:56.916
Tally‐ho!
[ Laughs ]

06:59.878 --> 07:01.338
Janet.

07:01.338 --> 07:02.464
Jimmy, it's Janet
from the insurance company.

07:02.464 --> 07:03.715
Here?

07:03.715 --> 07:05.508
You love horses, too,
and you come to this stable?

07:05.508 --> 07:08.345
What are the chances?
One in 3,058.

07:08.345 --> 07:09.888
How refreshingly literal.

07:09.888 --> 07:12.015
Of course,
if you don't care for horses

07:12.015 --> 07:14.351
and you're just trying
to curry favor to help your son,

07:14.351 --> 07:15.769
then that is
a different calculation.

07:15.769 --> 07:16.978
Oh, I'm here to ride.

07:16.978 --> 07:18.897
I love these...
things.

07:18.897 --> 07:20.440
Yeah, our son?

07:20.440 --> 07:23.109
Why would you bring
that non‐horse into this?

07:23.109 --> 07:26.404
I was just gonna go for a ride.
Mind if I join you?

07:26.404 --> 07:27.572
Mm.

07:27.572 --> 07:28.948
I'll just get my horse.

07:28.948 --> 07:30.241
[ Quietly ] Don't have one,
definitely can't ride one.

07:30.241 --> 07:31.326
[ Quietly ] Shut up!

07:31.326 --> 07:32.243
Right.

07:32.243 --> 07:33.787
Oh. Hello.

07:33.787 --> 07:35.038
Hello, h‐hello there.

07:35.038 --> 07:37.707
How ‐‐ Come ‐‐ Come along,
out of your house.

07:37.707 --> 07:38.458
Come along.

07:38.458 --> 07:40.585
Walking out...
my horse.

07:40.585 --> 07:42.212
Come along. There we are,
there we are, there we are.

07:42.212 --> 07:43.088
Now stop.

07:43.088 --> 07:44.756
Put my foot
in the handle.

07:44.756 --> 07:45.882
Give us a jog up.

07:45.882 --> 07:47.592
One, two, three. Oi!

07:47.592 --> 07:48.760
Ooh!

07:48.760 --> 07:50.679
I'm gonna do everything I can
to connect

07:50.679 --> 07:52.389
with that horse‐loving robot.

07:52.389 --> 07:54.432
You check her purse,
take a look at her car,

07:54.432 --> 07:56.017
and see if there's anything else
we can bond over.

07:56.017 --> 07:57.977
So purse snatcher,
horse thief.

07:57.977 --> 07:59.145
Yes.
Got it.

07:59.145 --> 08:01.773
Mom powers. Right.

08:01.773 --> 08:03.525
Come on, Maya,
you can do it.

08:03.525 --> 08:06.569
Love your son enough to be good
at riding. Please.

08:06.569 --> 08:08.947
Come along, then.
This way, this way.

08:08.947 --> 08:11.032
Holy crap! I'm good!

08:12.492 --> 08:13.993
Hey!

08:13.993 --> 08:16.371
Are you friends
with a Donald Bronson?

08:16.371 --> 08:18.206
"Who?"
That's what
I thought.

08:18.206 --> 08:20.875
He gave a whole speech
about how you're his hero.

08:20.875 --> 08:23.044
He said you're the bravest guy
he knows,

08:23.044 --> 08:24.796
you make him
a better person.

08:24.796 --> 08:27.924
"Now I'm someone else's
speech?"

08:27.924 --> 08:30.301
"Stupid I‐N‐S ‐‐

08:30.301 --> 08:33.221
inspiration porn."
What's that?

08:33.221 --> 08:35.223
It's a portrayal of people
with disabilities

08:35.223 --> 08:37.183
as one‐dimensional saints
who only exist

08:37.183 --> 08:40.145
to warm the hearts and open
the minds of able‐bodied people.

08:40.145 --> 08:42.147
"I blame Tiny Tim."

08:42.147 --> 08:43.690
It's terrible,

08:43.690 --> 08:46.443
but it's great for winning
essay contests, damn it!

08:46.443 --> 08:48.737
I'm over here trying to sell
Albert Einstein.

08:48.737 --> 08:51.281
Hey, it's not Donald's fault
you picked Einstein.

08:51.281 --> 08:53.908
Come on, man,
play to win.

08:53.908 --> 08:56.119
"Let's talk to Donald."

08:56.119 --> 08:57.704
Sounds good.

08:57.704 --> 09:00.915
[ Mockingly ]
Ugh! Einstein is my hero.

09:00.915 --> 09:03.168
He was
a lowly patent clerk.

09:03.168 --> 09:05.003
[ Snores ]

09:05.003 --> 09:06.504
[ Normal voice ]
Come on, dude.

09:06.504 --> 09:07.881
[ Laughs ]

09:07.881 --> 09:10.925
What is it
about riding horses

09:10.925 --> 09:16.306
that makes me want to discuss
interests other than horses?

09:16.306 --> 09:17.640
No?

09:17.640 --> 09:19.392
Horses it is.
Giddyup.

09:19.392 --> 09:20.518
Ooh, not really. No.

09:20.518 --> 09:23.480
I must say,
your Trakehner is beautiful.

09:23.480 --> 09:25.148
You two really have
great chemistry.

09:25.148 --> 09:27.609
Yeah, we have
quite a bond.

09:27.609 --> 09:29.277
Do you do dressage
with him?

09:29.277 --> 09:30.653
Dressage?
Mm.

09:30.653 --> 09:32.030
Of course.

09:32.030 --> 09:33.698
I'm not gonna have
a perfectly good Trakehner

09:33.698 --> 09:36.534
and not do dressage with him ‐‐
<i>on</i> him, Janet.

09:36.534 --> 09:38.369
I just love dressage.

09:38.369 --> 09:39.537
Who doesn't?

09:39.537 --> 09:41.331
Oh, it's all
I love to do.

09:41.331 --> 09:43.416
Oh, would you
show me some, please?

09:43.416 --> 09:45.668
Oh...

09:45.668 --> 09:46.753
[ Car alarm chirps ]
Ooh.

09:50.507 --> 09:52.092
Bingo.

09:52.092 --> 09:54.052
Oh, my God.

09:54.052 --> 09:55.470
I matter.

09:55.470 --> 09:56.679
I matter.

09:56.679 --> 09:57.764
I matter!

09:57.764 --> 09:59.140
Right.

09:59.140 --> 10:02.894
I'm, uh, I'm gonna do
some dressage now...

10:02.894 --> 10:03.895
per your request.

10:03.895 --> 10:06.523
Honey. We got to go.
We're late.

10:06.523 --> 10:10.318
We got to pick up our daughter
from <i>track</i> practice.

10:10.318 --> 10:11.444
Track? Oh!

10:11.444 --> 10:13.321
<i>My</i> daughter runs track.

10:13.321 --> 10:14.280
You're a track mom.

10:14.280 --> 10:16.699
I am.
I'm a track mom.

10:16.699 --> 10:18.284
What school?
Dylan goes to Lafayette.

10:18.284 --> 10:19.577
Dylan DiMeo?

10:19.577 --> 10:21.538
Yes.
Do you know her?

10:21.538 --> 10:23.581
My daughter races against her
all the time.

10:23.581 --> 10:25.375
She says she's amazing.

10:25.375 --> 10:26.417
[ Whispering ] Yes!

10:26.417 --> 10:28.670
[ Normal voice ]
What a small world. Wow.

10:28.670 --> 10:30.255
Oh, yeah, definitely,
l‐let's get off these big,

10:30.255 --> 10:32.549
beautiful,
not scary animals

10:32.549 --> 10:36.010
and go far from them
and discuss.

10:36.010 --> 10:37.137
Ugh!
No, no.
Wait, wait, wait.

10:37.137 --> 10:38.596
Your dressage.

10:38.596 --> 10:39.973
Oh, no, we don't have to do
that anymore.

10:39.973 --> 10:42.058
We've got something new.
It's better.

10:42.058 --> 10:43.810
Oh, tell her
to do some dressage for me.

10:43.810 --> 10:45.145
Yeah, honey.

10:45.145 --> 10:47.272
What is dressage,
after all, but...

10:47.272 --> 10:50.233
dancing...for horses?

10:52.569 --> 10:54.445
All right, I'm...

10:54.445 --> 10:57.240
I'm not gonna do a lot.

10:57.240 --> 10:58.825
Okay, buddy, here I go.

11:00.577 --> 11:03.580
♪♪

11:03.580 --> 11:05.415
W‐What are you doing?

11:05.415 --> 11:07.375
I'm doing your bloody dressage,
aren't I?

11:07.375 --> 11:09.335
Oh, no,
the <i>horse</i> dances.

11:10.628 --> 11:12.589
Yeah, I'm getting
to that part.

11:12.589 --> 11:13.923
What is happening?

11:13.923 --> 11:16.634
Can you please give my son
a better wheelchair?

11:16.634 --> 11:18.553
Ugh!
I knew it.

11:18.553 --> 11:20.388
Fine.
I know it was wrong.

11:20.388 --> 11:23.391
But I will do anything
for my... son.

11:23.391 --> 11:24.726
That's dressage,
isn't it?

11:24.726 --> 11:26.102
I mean, I know we've got
other things to discuss,

11:26.102 --> 11:27.687
but that is
bloody amazing.

11:27.687 --> 11:29.689
Look, your daughter
<i>is</i> Dylan DiMeo, right?

11:29.689 --> 11:31.107
She is. That part
is actually true.

11:31.107 --> 11:32.609
God, it still feels like
I'm lying.

11:32.609 --> 11:35.486
My daughter Melissa
races against her tomorrow.

11:35.486 --> 11:37.113
She's never won a race.

11:37.113 --> 11:39.157
Dylan has won
every single time.

11:39.157 --> 11:40.700
Okay.
Just saying ‐‐

11:40.700 --> 11:44.954
if Melissa could win once,
it would make her year,

11:44.954 --> 11:47.332
and then I would owe you.

11:47.332 --> 11:50.251
Are you suggesting that I tell
my daughter to throw the race?

11:50.251 --> 11:51.711
I can't do that.

11:51.711 --> 11:55.006
Then there's nothing
I can do for you.

11:55.006 --> 11:56.925
"Dancing for horses" ‐‐

11:56.925 --> 11:58.635
Yeah, I see

11:58.635 --> 12:00.386
where I could have phrased that
a little more clearly.

12:00.386 --> 12:01.596
♪♪

12:01.596 --> 12:03.640
[ Indistinct conversations ]

12:03.640 --> 12:05.850
Hello, Donald.

12:05.850 --> 12:07.810
Please ‐‐
have a seat.

12:10.480 --> 12:12.899
A little birdie told us
about a certain speech.

12:12.899 --> 12:14.108
Funny thing
about speeches ‐‐

12:14.108 --> 12:15.735
you kind of need teeth
to give them.

12:16.945 --> 12:18.738
"Chill the hell out."

12:18.738 --> 12:19.906
Oh.

12:19.906 --> 12:21.199
Listen,
about the speech ‐‐

12:21.199 --> 12:23.243
I know that I called you
my friend,

12:23.243 --> 12:24.827
which, you know,
that ‐‐ that may be a stretch,

12:24.827 --> 12:27.956
but I honestly do see you
as a friend.

12:27.956 --> 12:30.208
A friend from...afar.

12:30.208 --> 12:32.126
JJ only has one friend
from afar ‐‐

12:32.126 --> 12:33.795
his pen pal Diego.

12:33.795 --> 12:35.088
And you ain't Diego.

12:36.005 --> 12:38.424
"It's I‐N‐S ‐‐

12:38.424 --> 12:39.550
insulting."

12:39.550 --> 12:41.261
I don't E‐X ‐‐

12:41.261 --> 12:46.099
exist to make you feel better
about yourself."

12:46.099 --> 12:49.185
Look! It's JJ and Donald,
the two friends!

12:49.185 --> 12:51.562
The hero
and the scribe.

12:51.562 --> 12:54.565
Oh, JJ, I'm so glad
I got to hear Donald's speech.

12:54.565 --> 12:57.151
I used to think of you
as just a person,

12:57.151 --> 12:58.903
but you are
so much more.

12:58.903 --> 13:00.655
You're a saint.

13:00.655 --> 13:02.865
And if <i>you</i> can do it,
<i>I</i> can do it.

13:02.865 --> 13:03.866
Do what?

13:05.159 --> 13:06.828
I'm not sure.

13:06.828 --> 13:09.831
♪♪

13:09.831 --> 13:12.583
Okay, I get it. I can see
how that would be insulting.

13:12.583 --> 13:15.295
"So you'll change
your speech?"

13:15.295 --> 13:16.421
Oh, no.

13:16.421 --> 13:18.423
No, I, uh, I want
to get into Pomona.

13:18.423 --> 13:21.592
I'm trying to get my
US News Top Regional Schools on.

13:21.592 --> 13:25.096
So I'm gonna need to win
this thing, and I'm going to.

13:25.096 --> 13:28.057
"Oh, are you?"

13:28.057 --> 13:30.810
<i>I'm</i> gonna win
the essay contest?

13:30.810 --> 13:32.812
How?
My speech sucks.

13:32.812 --> 13:35.857
"Give one about me."

13:35.857 --> 13:38.026
"Beat Donald's...

13:38.026 --> 13:39.235
ass."

13:39.235 --> 13:41.029
Oh, yeah!
High‐five me, bro.

13:41.029 --> 13:43.614
You really <i>are</i> my hero.

13:43.614 --> 13:45.324
Ugh! I hate you!

13:45.324 --> 13:48.995
What kind of monster
asks a 12‐year‐old girl

13:48.995 --> 13:51.330
to throw a race?

13:51.330 --> 13:52.623
So that's it, then?

13:52.623 --> 13:55.501
JJ's just stuck with
whatever this lady gives him?

13:55.501 --> 13:57.712
Dylan: No, he's not.

13:57.712 --> 13:59.630
Dylan?
Where are you?

13:59.630 --> 14:00.798
The hall.

14:00.798 --> 14:03.259
The walls in this house
are crazy‐thin.

14:03.259 --> 14:04.635
Hi.

14:04.635 --> 14:06.512
I was in the yard for the
beginning of this conversation.

14:06.512 --> 14:08.931
Dylan, no.
Just one race.

14:08.931 --> 14:11.225
I see how much you do for JJ,
and I can never help,

14:11.225 --> 14:12.351
but now I <i>can.</i>

14:12.351 --> 14:13.561
I want to.

14:13.561 --> 14:14.729
Are you sure?

14:14.729 --> 14:16.647
Yeah.

14:16.647 --> 14:20.068
So, I guess
I'm gonna lose tomorrow.

14:20.068 --> 14:21.736
What does losing
feel like?

14:21.736 --> 14:22.653
Does it hurt?

14:22.653 --> 14:24.072
Only at first.

14:24.072 --> 14:25.114
Yeah,
you get used to it.

14:29.619 --> 14:32.455
Okay, time to write the most
epic, moving speech of all time.

14:32.455 --> 14:33.664
What should I do?

14:33.664 --> 14:36.042
"Make people cry

14:36.042 --> 14:39.212
and give me P‐I‐T ‐‐
What?

14:39.212 --> 14:42.131
"... pity looks and E‐N‐C ‐‐

14:42.131 --> 14:44.926
encouraging pats
on the arm ‐‐

14:44.926 --> 14:47.595
all the stuff I hate."

14:47.595 --> 14:49.263
I'm doing this for you,
hoverboard.

14:49.263 --> 14:51.057
I mean... JJ.

14:51.057 --> 14:54.060
[ Typing ]
"No matter where I go,

14:54.060 --> 14:56.813
there's one person
who is always at my side,

14:56.813 --> 14:58.606
even when I'm alone ‐‐

14:58.606 --> 15:00.149
my brother, JJ."

15:00.149 --> 15:03.903
"Now make me
happy all the time."

15:03.903 --> 15:07.740
"All I want is to help
the able‐bodied

15:07.740 --> 15:09.826
learn and grow."

15:09.826 --> 15:12.036
Hey! This is
the Magical Negro!

15:13.246 --> 15:14.789
You know,
like in the movies

15:14.789 --> 15:16.874
where the black character's
just there

15:16.874 --> 15:18.793
to help the white guy
on <i>his</i> journey

15:18.793 --> 15:21.129
and he mainly speaks
in folksy sayings.

15:21.129 --> 15:24.006
"Eh, don't know much
about blah‐blah,

15:24.006 --> 15:26.217
but a man's gotta have
a blah."

15:26.217 --> 15:27.135
[ Chuckles ]

15:27.135 --> 15:30.054
"We both get C‐L‐I‐C ‐‐

15:30.054 --> 15:31.097
clichés."

15:31.097 --> 15:32.390
We sure do, buddy.

15:32.390 --> 15:34.142
Hey, Ray, turn around.

15:34.142 --> 15:35.977
We're gonna do that thing
where you turn back

15:35.977 --> 15:37.937
and we're suddenly gone,
as if by magic.

15:37.937 --> 15:41.023
Can we do this another time?
The contest is tomorrow.

15:41.023 --> 15:42.275
Let's write my speech.

15:42.275 --> 15:44.402
We'll have our fun
later, JJ.

15:44.402 --> 15:46.154
Able‐bodied white guy
calling.

15:46.154 --> 15:47.530
♪♪

15:47.530 --> 15:49.824
"Sure,
JJ doesn't walk.

15:49.824 --> 15:52.410
Who needs to walk
when you can soar?"

15:52.410 --> 15:56.789
"Courage is a two‐letter word
spelled JJ."

15:56.789 --> 16:00.751
"JJ might be skinny,
but he's got a big, fat asset ‐‐

16:00.751 --> 16:01.919
his heart."

16:03.462 --> 16:05.214
Oh, mine are bad
but yours were good?

16:05.214 --> 16:07.008
Own the stage.

16:07.008 --> 16:08.676
Feel the words.

16:08.676 --> 16:10.803
"JJ is my hero!"

16:10.803 --> 16:11.846
Okay, now you.

16:13.973 --> 16:16.601
[ Voice cracking ]
JJ is my hero!

16:18.144 --> 16:19.812
Okay, try it again,
but weirder.

16:19.812 --> 16:21.647
I just want to see
if it's possible.

16:21.647 --> 16:22.857
♪♪

16:22.857 --> 16:25.151
Unique New York.
Unique New York.

16:25.151 --> 16:27.320
Unique New York.

16:27.320 --> 16:30.072
Go out there and win this.

16:30.072 --> 16:31.908
Go out there and lose this.

16:31.908 --> 16:34.327
What's the point, Mom?
I always lose.

16:34.327 --> 16:38.372
Well, I have a feeling
today is going to be your day.

16:38.372 --> 16:40.708
How do you feel about
our daughter doing this?

16:40.708 --> 16:42.084
Proud.

16:42.084 --> 16:45.421
Like a dark, sickening abyss
of pride.

16:45.421 --> 16:47.506
Yeah, right here.
It's...
Mm.

16:47.506 --> 16:49.842
glorious.

16:49.842 --> 16:51.761
Man: On your mark,
get set...

16:51.761 --> 16:52.970
[ Starter pistol fires ]

16:52.970 --> 16:54.805
[ Spectators cheering ]

16:54.805 --> 16:58.684
My family is different
from other families.

16:58.684 --> 17:01.479
16 years ago,
my brother, JJ,

17:01.479 --> 17:04.232
was diagnosed
with cerebral palsy.

17:04.232 --> 17:06.984
And even though
I wasn't even born yet,

17:06.984 --> 17:10.863
that moment made me
the man I am today.

17:10.863 --> 17:11.697
[ Students murmuring ]

17:11.697 --> 17:13.199
Go, go. Come on.

17:14.575 --> 17:15.868
Go!

17:15.868 --> 17:17.703
[ Spectators cheering ]

17:17.703 --> 17:18.704
You can do this!

17:18.704 --> 17:20.498
Move your body!

17:20.498 --> 17:22.083
Come on!

17:23.709 --> 17:26.128
Smell the trophy!
Be the trophy!

17:29.048 --> 17:31.133
Dylan!
What are you doing?!

17:32.510 --> 17:34.554
Is it hard sometimes?

17:34.554 --> 17:35.972
Sure.

17:35.972 --> 17:40.059
But JJ knows in his heart

17:40.059 --> 17:43.229
that the only real disability
in life

17:43.229 --> 17:45.731
[voice breaking]
is a bad attitude.

17:45.731 --> 17:46.941
That's true.

17:46.941 --> 17:50.027
And that is
what makes him so ‐‐

17:54.156 --> 17:55.491
[ Whispering ] "Brave."

17:55.491 --> 17:56.826
[ Sighs ]

17:56.826 --> 17:58.244
I can't do this.

17:58.244 --> 17:59.495
She can't do this.

18:01.330 --> 18:02.415
Run, Dylan!

18:02.415 --> 18:03.457
Run!

18:03.457 --> 18:04.917
Run!
Run!

18:04.917 --> 18:07.003
Go! Don't let her beat you,
little girl!
Just run!

18:07.003 --> 18:09.880
Do it!
Screw it! Run!

18:09.880 --> 18:11.507
Go on!

18:11.507 --> 18:13.551
Come on, Dylan,
you can do it!

18:13.551 --> 18:15.720
Go on, darling! Run!

18:15.720 --> 18:17.263
Go on, darling!
Run!

18:17.263 --> 18:18.806
Come on!

18:18.806 --> 18:20.474
She's gonna win!

18:20.474 --> 18:21.267
Yes!

18:21.267 --> 18:22.476
[ Spectators cheering ]

18:24.770 --> 18:26.647
My brother isn't a hero.

18:26.647 --> 18:28.316
[ Whispering ]
This feels off‐message.

18:28.316 --> 18:30.109
I know him
better than anyone.

18:30.109 --> 18:32.153
And I can tell you,
in all honesty,

18:32.153 --> 18:34.238
he can be a real jerk.

18:34.238 --> 18:36.282
He teases me and tortures me,

18:36.282 --> 18:38.326
runs me over
with his wheelchair.

18:38.326 --> 18:42.121
He told me I was adopted
and my real mom was Nancy Grace!

18:42.121 --> 18:43.748
[ Snorts, laughs ]
Nice.

18:43.748 --> 18:46.584
He isn't brave, either.
He's just living his life.

18:46.584 --> 18:49.337
And there's nothing brave
about that.

18:49.337 --> 18:52.256
[ Scattered light applause ]

18:52.256 --> 18:53.966
That did not
make me feel good.

18:55.176 --> 18:57.011
Whoo!

18:59.180 --> 19:00.723
Congrats, champ.

19:00.723 --> 19:03.684
I could have lost.
It was just one race.

19:03.684 --> 19:04.935
Oh, darling, no.

19:04.935 --> 19:07.021
I tasted it
for a second ‐‐ defeat.

19:07.021 --> 19:08.898
I did <i>not</i> care for it.

19:08.898 --> 19:10.024
Put it behind you.

19:10.024 --> 19:12.610
I promise ‐‐
you will never lose again.

19:12.610 --> 19:14.487
Sure. That's a thing
we can promise.

19:14.487 --> 19:16.822
Not only did Melissa lose,
but for a second,

19:16.822 --> 19:19.325
she thought she was going to win
and <i>then</i> she lost.

19:19.325 --> 19:20.493
She's never
getting over this.

19:20.493 --> 19:22.286
Yeah, we should never
have agreed ‐‐

19:22.286 --> 19:23.621
I don't have time
for this, okay?

19:23.621 --> 19:24.997
I have to find
my daughter.

19:24.997 --> 19:26.207
Ooh, let me check
her usual spot.

19:27.416 --> 19:28.501
Nah, she's not
behind Dylan.

19:28.501 --> 19:29.960
[ Scoffs ]

19:29.960 --> 19:31.879
Go on. Go and celebrate
with your friends.

19:31.879 --> 19:33.089
[ Sighing ]
We'll find a way.

19:33.089 --> 19:34.757
Oh, I know we will.

19:34.757 --> 19:36.842
And in the meantime,
our integrity's intact,

19:36.842 --> 19:40.137
and that is the best gift
we can give JJ.

19:40.137 --> 19:42.932
And, time permitting,
our other children.

19:42.932 --> 19:44.308
[ School bell rings ]

19:44.308 --> 19:45.726
And the winner ‐‐

19:45.726 --> 19:48.771
not to be rude
to all the... losers,

19:48.771 --> 19:50.981
but let's just
say it all together.

19:50.981 --> 19:53.275
All: Donald Bronson!

19:53.275 --> 19:56.654
Dr. Miller:
Yay, Donald! Oh!

19:56.654 --> 19:57.822
Whoo!

19:57.822 --> 19:59.156
This is for you, JJ!

19:59.156 --> 20:00.908
Thanks, Donald.

20:00.908 --> 20:01.742
Let's go.

20:03.494 --> 20:05.413
Hey! How'd the speech go,
Ray?

20:05.413 --> 20:07.039
[ Chuckles ]
No one liked it.

20:07.039 --> 20:09.083
Kenneth!
No, it's true.
No one did.

20:09.083 --> 20:10.876
"I liked it."

20:10.876 --> 20:13.504
Oh! Mrs. DiMeo!
I'm so glad I caught you.

20:13.504 --> 20:15.005
I was looking for Melissa,

20:15.005 --> 20:19.677
when I heard the most heartfelt,
honest words about your JJ.

20:19.677 --> 20:24.014
His friendship with that Donald
is such an inspiration.

20:24.014 --> 20:27.393
Call me. We'll make sure
JJ gets what he needs.

20:27.393 --> 20:29.186
Yeah, thanks, Janet!

20:29.186 --> 20:31.647
Let's have dinner
with Donald soon!

20:31.647 --> 20:32.898
We still have
our integrity, right?

20:32.898 --> 20:34.024
Enough of it.

20:34.024 --> 20:36.318
"God bless us...

20:36.318 --> 20:37.903
every one."

20:43.200 --> 20:44.452
In the end, that boy got
the wheelchair he deserved.

20:44.452 --> 20:46.203
Can you please
stop doing that?

20:46.203 --> 20:49.498
His brother didn't win
that speaking contest,

20:49.498 --> 20:51.625
but he walked away with
something more important ‐‐

20:51.625 --> 20:53.169
his soul.

20:53.169 --> 20:55.463
These kids over here?
Well, they're making out.

20:55.463 --> 20:57.882
And that kid? He wears
the same shirt every day.

20:57.882 --> 21:00.926
And ol' Kenneth? Well [chuckles]
he turned out just fine.

21:00.926 --> 21:02.303
Fall turned to winter,

21:02.303 --> 21:05.055
and a stiff breeze
blew ol' Kenneth away ‐‐

21:05.055 --> 21:09.101
[ Echoing ] if he was
ever there at all.
